First the practice of dealing less strictly with the convention of Indissolubility beginning in the 19th Century caused a contradiction. Then the positive precepts from Decretum Gratianum, promulgated as the Gratian text byAngelicus in 1140, became opposed by the views of Thomas Aquinas in the 13th Century who placed marriage equal to religion due to copying his Benedictine Catholic ways. Thirdly, from this clash of views on marriage came several contradictory literatures. In particular, as the State joined in marriage so that there by societal changes witnessed clear advances in feminism as well as the problems of domestic violence, rates of depression, libido, marital violence and anti-social behavior once attributed solely to broken families, began to concern considerably.
Moreover as the individual's right to freedom was considered more and more of a human right, the individual's right to divorce also flourished.
